\id XXA STO1 
\h GURRE KAMILAROI 
\toc1 GURRE KAMILAROI: OR KAMILAROI SAYINGS 
\toc2 GURRE KAMILAROI 
\mt1 GURRE KAMILAROI: OR KAMILAROI SAYINGS  
\pc BY  
\pc WILLIAM RIDLEY, MISSIONARY.  
\pc ILLUSTRATIONS BY W. MASON.  
\pc “To whom he was not spoken of, they shall see; and they who have not heard shall understand.”—Paul to Romans, xv., 21.  
\p  
\pc SYDNEY: PRINTED AT THE EMPIRE GENERAL STEAM PRINTING OFFICE, 172, GEORGE STREET.  
\p  
\pc 1856.  
\c 1  
\s1 Gurre Kamilaroi.  
\p Kamilaroi is the language spoken by the aborigines along the Namoi River, on part of the Bundarra and Balun, and 200 miles of the Barwan (or Darling); also on Liverpool Plains, and about the head of the Hunter.  
\p The writer believes that any one who carefully reads through this Key, especially the first 2 pages, will be able to pronounce the foregoing Kamilaroi sentences, and teach the aborigines to read them. Many of the aborigines, especially the young men, are very quick at learning to read.  
\p It is very important that the rule of naming the letters according to their pronunciation in words should be attended to, as it will remove great difficulties from the way of beginners. How could an ignorant person guess that the letter called “double you” had the sound w in wit? or that “aitch” was merely a hard breathing?  
\p The Christian into whose hands this little book may come, and who has any aborigines speaking kamilaroi near, is earnestly requested to consider, whether it is not worth a patient and prayerful effort to teach them to read those precious saving truths which are dimly and scantily, but in some measure really, expressed in these brief sentences.  
\c 2  
\s1 KEY to the foregoing “Kamilaroi speech.”  
\s2 RULES OF PRONUNCIATION.  
\p Pronounce ā as a in father  
\p a as a in mat  
\p ē as ey in obey  
\p e as e in net  
\p ī as i in marine  
\p i as i in it  
\p ō as o in bone  
\p o as o in on  
\p ū as oo in moon  
\p u as u in bun  
\p ai as i in wine  
\p ao as ow in how  
\p oi as oi in noise  
\p g always as in go  
\p ŋ as ng in ring.  
\c 3  
\p In English we use the sound ŋ or ng only at the end of a syllable; its frequent occurrence at the beginning of a syllable in Kamilaroi is therefore a slight, but only a slight difficulty. It is only necessary to use precisely the same consonant sound which we have in ring, sing, &c., with a vowel after and not before it.  
\p N.B. Name the letters as they are pronounced; that is, call g \bd ge\bd* (as in get), h \bd he\bd*, ŋ \bd eng\bd*, r \bd re\bd*, w \bd we\bd*, and y \bd ye\bd*. Thus the name will guide the learner to the proper sound in spelling.  
\s1 letters  
\p \bd a b d e g h i j k l m n ŋ o p r t u v w y ai ao oi\bd*  
\s1 names and kinship terms  
\p ippai, murri, kubbi, kumbo. (names of men;)  
\p ippata, mata, kapota, buta. (names of women;)  
\p yarai, gille, taon, wī, boiyoi. (sun, moon, earth, fire, pennyroyal (herb).)  
\p giwīr, īnar, birrī, miē. (man, woman, boy, girl.)  
\p kaiŋal, buba, ŋumba.(child, father, mother.)  
\p wurume, ŋummuŋā.(son, daughter.)  
\p daiādi, bōādi.(brother, sister.)  
\c 4  
\m \bd Baiame gīr yarai, gille, mirri, taon ellibu gimobi.\bd*  
\p God verily sun, moon, stars, earth also made.  
\p  
\m \bd Baiame yalwuŋa murruba; Baiame minnaminnabul\bd*  
\m \bd ŋummilda, minnaminnabul wīnuŋulda.\bd*  
\p God always is good; God everything  
\p sees, everything hears.  
\p  
\m \bd Baiame gīr kānuŋo kubba, kūnial, maian, tulu,\bd*  
\m \bd yindal, beran, boiyoi gimobi.\bd*  
\p God verily every hill, plain, watercourse, tree,  
\p grass, beran (a herb), pennyroyal made.  
\p  
\m \bd Baiame gīr yārāman, būrumo, bundar, mūte, dūli,\bd*  
\m \bd dīnoun, buralga, biloela, millimumul, gulamboli, kobado,\bd*  
\m \bd mullion, guiya, nūrai, ŋundoba, burulu, muŋin, kānuŋo\bd*  
\m \bd di gombi.\bd*  
\p God verily horse, dog, kangaroo, opossum, goanna,  
\p emu, native companion, cockatoo, swallow, pelican, parrot,  
\p eagle, fish, brown snake, deadly black snake, flies, mosquitoes, all  
\p animals made.  
\c 5  
\m \bd Baiame gīr giwīr gimobi; mal giwīr Adam. Baiame\bd*  
\m \bd goë: “Kamil murruba giwīr ŋāndil ŋuddelago; ŋaia\bd*  
\m \bd giwīrgo īnar gimbille.” Īla Baiame īnar gimobi; mal\bd*  
\m \bd īnar Īv: Īv gulīr Adamu.\bd*  
\p God verily man made; first man Adam. God  
\p said, “Not good man alone for to dwell; I  
\p for man woman will make.” Then God woman made; first  
\p woman Eve; Eve wife of Adam.  
\p  
\m \bd Adam buba murriŋu, buba wundaŋu, buba kānuŋo:\bd*  
\m \bd Īv ŋumba murriŋu, ŋumba wundaŋu, ŋumba kānuŋo.\bd*  
\p Adam is father of the blackfellows, father of the whites, father of all:  
\p Eve the mother of blacks, mother of whites, mother of all.  
\c 6  
\m \bd Adam Īv ellibu warawara yanani. Kanuŋo giwīr\bd*  
\m \bd kānuŋo īnar warawara yanani, kānuŋo kagil ginyi.\bd*  
\m \bd Baiame yili ginyi, goe, “Kānuŋo giwīr, kānuŋo īnar\bd*  
\m \bd warawara yanani, kānuŋo kagil ginyi, ŋaia ŋārma bālu\bd*  
\m \bd bumāle.” Immanuel, wurume Baiameŋu, goe “Kamil.\bd*  
\m \bd Kamil ŋinda ŋārma bumala, ŋinda ŋunna bumala, ŋaia\bd*  
\m \bd balugi, giwīr īnar moron gigigo.”\bd*  
\p Adam, Eve also, astray went. All men  
\p all women astray went, all bad became.  
\p God angry became, he said “All men, all women,  
\p astray are gone, all bad have become. I them dead  
\p will smite.” Immanuel, Son of God, said “Not so.  
\p Not thou them smite; Thou me smite, I  
\p will die; man, woman, alive for to be.”  
\c 7  
\m \bd Immanuel ŋeanekūnda Baiame: ŋerma Baiame giwīr\bd*  
\m \bd ginyi. Murruba immanuel; kamil ŋaragedūl murruba\bd*  
\m \bd yealokwai ŋerma.\bd*  
\p Immanuel with us God: he God man  
\p became. Good is Immanuel; not another is good like him.  
\p  
\m \bd Īlambo Immanuel taongo tai-yanani, giwīr ginyi.\bd*  
\m \bd ŋērma gīr burula wībil murruba gimobi, burula mūga murruba\bd*  
\m \bd gimobi, burula mūga-binna murruba gimobi.\bd*  
\p Long ago Immanuel to earth came, man he became.  
\p He verily many sick well made, many blind  
\p well made, many deaf well made.  
\c 8  
\m \bd Giwīr\bd*  
\m \bd kair Layāru. Ŋerŋu bular boādi, māri, māta. Layaru wibil\bd*  
\m \bd ginyi. Bular boādi gurre wāala Immanuelgo, goaldendai,\bd*  
\m \bd “Ŋai daiadi, ŋinnu layaru, wibil.” Kamil yanani Immanuel.\bd*  
\m \bd Yerāla layaru balūni. Bularbularo bābine bālūn\bd*  
\m \bd taonda. Īla Immanuel taiyanani. Mari māta ellibu\bd*  
\m \bd yūgillona. Immanuel goe, “Ŋinnu daiadi yealo moron\bd*  
\m \bd gigi.” Burula giwir burula inar yugillona. Immanuel\bd*  
\m \bd daonmago yanani. Yārul daonma kundawi; Immanuel\bd*  
\m \bd goe “Ŋindai ārul diomulla” ŋarma gīr yarul diome.\bd*  
\m \bd Immanuel kākūldone “Layaru taiyanuŋa.” Ī Layaru\bd*  
\m \bd moron ginyi, taiyanani. Bular boadi burul guiyē.\bd*  
\p A man  
\p name Lazarus. Belonging to him two sisters Mary, Marta. Lazarus sick  
\p became. The two sisters word sent to Immanuel, saying,  
\p “My brother, Thy Lazarus, is sick.” Not went Immanuel.  
\p By and bye Lazarus died. Four days he lay dead  
\p in the ground. Then Immanuel came. Mary, Martha also  
\p were weeping. Immanuel said “Your brother again alive  
\p shall be.” Many men, many women, were weeping. Immanuel  
\p to the grave went; a stone the grave covered; Immanuel  
\p said “Ye the stone take away.” They the stone lifted up.  
\p Immanuel cried aloud “Lazarus come forth.” Then Lazarus  
\p alive became, he came forth. The two sisters were very glad.  
\c 9  
\m \fig Jairus Daughter|src="Jairus Daughter.JPG" size="col" ref="GURRE KAMILAROI 9:0" \fig*  
\m \bd Ŋaragedūli miēdūl wībil ginyi; ŋumba boiyoi wune;\bd*  
\m \bd kamil miedul murruba ginyi; murru ginyi wibil, ŋullimun\bd*  
\m \bd balūni. Buba yanani Immanuel ŋummillego; gir\bd*  
\m \bd ŋummi; goe, “Inda barai taiyanuŋa, murruba gimbildi\bd*  
\m \bd ŋai miedul. Ŋai miedul burul wibil ŋullimun baluni;\bd*  
\m \bd inda taiyanuŋa ŋai kūndigo.” Immanuel goe,\bd*  
\m \bd “Ŋulle yanoai kundigo.” Ila yanani bular\bd*  
\m \bd kundigo. Ŋumba duri, yugillona, goe “Ŋii! Ŋii! Ŋai\bd*  
\m \bd miedul baluni.” Burula īnar yugillona goe “Ŋii!\bd*  
\m \bd miedul baluni.” Immanuel goe “Kurria yūŋa. kamil\bd*  
\m \bd miedul baluni; yeal babillona.” Burulabu gindami;\bd*  
\m \bd ŋārma gīr balundai wīnuŋi. Immanuel murra kawāni\bd*  
\m \bd miedul, goe, “Miēdūl waria.” Īla miedul moron ginyi,\bd*  
\m \bd warine, gurre goe. Ŋumba, buba ellibu, burul guiye.\bd*  
\p At another time a little girl sick became; the mother pennyroyal gave;  
\p not the little girl well became; much she grew sick, almost  
\p dead. The father went Immanuel to see; truly  
\p he found him; he said “Thou quickly come, well make  
\p my little girl. My little girl is very sick, almost dead;  
\p you come to my house.” Immanuel said  
\p “We two will go to the House.” Then went the two  
\p to the house. The mother came, she wept, said “Alas! alas! my  
\p little girl is dead.” Many women were weeping, said “Alas!  
\p the little girl is dead.” Immanuel said “Cease weeping. Not  
\p the girl is dead; only she is asleep.” All of them laughed;  
\p they verily her to be dead knew. Immanuel by hand took  
\p the girl, said “damsel arise.” Then the girl alive became,  
\p arose, words spoke. The mother, father also, very glad.  
\c 10  
\m \fig Jesus Heals|src="Jesus Heals.JPG" size="col" ref="GURRE KAMILAROI 10:0" \fig*  
\m \bd Ŋarageduli bular giwir mūga ŋuddelona turrubulda\bd*  
\m \bd Immanuel aro yanani; bular muga wīnuŋi. Kākūldone,\bd*  
\m \bd “Immanuel, dūrunmi, wurume, Dāvidu ŋummilla!\bd*  
\m \bd ŋurrāga ŋeane.” Burula giwir goe “Kurria! kurria\bd*  
\m \bd ŋindai kakūllego.” Giwir muga yealo kakuldone\bd*  
\m \bd “Durunmi, wurume davidu, ŋummilla! Ŋurraga ŋeane.”\bd*  
\p Another time, two men blind sat by the way.  
\p Immanuel there came; the two blind heard, they cried aloud,  
\p “Immanuel, King, Son of David, look!  
\p Pity us.” Many people said “Have done! cease  
\p ye to cry aloud.” The men blind again cried aloud  
\p “King, Son of David, look! pity us!”  
\c 11  
\p  
\m \bd Ila Immanuel warine, goe “Minna ŋindai goalle? Minna\bd*  
\m \bd ŋaia murramulle?” ŋarma goe, “Durunmi, wuna\bd*  
\m \bd ŋeane ŋummildai.” Ila Immanuel ŋarma mil tāmūlda:\bd*  
\m \bd baianbu ŋarma murru ŋummillego.\bd*  
\p Then Immanuel stood still, said “What you will say? What  
\p I shall do?” They said “King, grant  
\p us to see.” Then Immanuel them eyes touches;  
\p instantly they are able to see.  
\c 12  
\m \fig Jesus Cross|src="Jesus Cross.JPG" size="col" ref="GURRE KAMILAROI 12:0" \fig*  
\m \bd Burula kagil giwir Immanuel kunmulta. Ŋarma\bd*  
\m \bd kaogo bindēa yulalle. Ŋarma gir tulu wīmi, ŋaragedul\bd*  
\m \bd tulu ŋanbīr wimi: ŋarma gir Immanuel wimi; murra\bd*  
\m \bd biru-dūni, dinna biru-dūni; tului wirri. Ŋarma tulu\bd*  
\m \bd tiome, Immanuel tului pindelundai. Yerāla Immanuel\bd*  
\m \bd baluni. Yerala giwir pilari turrur duni; gue dulirri.\bd*  
\p Many bad men Immanuel seized. They  
\p on his head thorns bound. They indeed a log laid, another  
\p log across they laid: they indeed Immanuel laid down; hands  
\p they pierced, feet they pierced; on cross fastened. They the cross  
\p raised, Immanuel on the cross hanging. Soon Immanuel  
\p died. Soon after a man with a spear his side pierced; blood flowed.  
\c 13  
\m \bd Bullului ŋarma gir Immanuel taonda wimi, kundawi.\bd*  
\m \bd Immanuel ŋūru bābine balūn taonda; yealo malo babine\bd*  
\m \bd balun taonda; yealo ŋaragedul ŋuru babine balun\bd*  
\m \bd taonda: ŋaragedul ŋuruko moron ginyi, warine.\bd*  
\p In evening they verily Immanuel in ground laid, covered.  
\p Immanuel the night lay dead in ground; also one day he lay  
\p dead in ground; also another night he lay dead  
\p in ground; next morning alive he became, arose.  
\p  
\m \bd Yerala gūnagullago yanani. \bd*  
\m \bd Yeladu Immanuel gunagullada ŋuddela: ŋerma\bd*  
\m \bd kanuŋo ŋummilda, kanuŋo wīnuŋulda.\bd*  
\p Soon after to heaven he went.  
\p Now Immanuel in heaven dwells; he  
\p all sees, all knows.  
\c 14  
\m \bd Murruba Immanuel; kamil ŋaragedul murruba\bd*  
\m \bd yealokwai ŋerma. Yerala Immanuel yealo taongo\bd*  
\m \bd taiyanille; ŋeane kanuŋo ŋummille. Immanuel kaia\bd*  
\m \bd goalle; ila kanuŋo balun, giwir, inar, kaiŋal, kanuŋo\bd*  
\m \bd moron gigi. Immanuel goalle “Minna inda gimobi?\bd*  
\m \bd Minna inda gimboi? Inda murruba gimobi? Inda\bd*  
\m \bd ŋununda taiyanuŋa gunagullago. Inda kagil gimobi?\bd*  
\m \bd Inda biru yanuŋa, urribū yanuŋa.”\bd*  
\p Good is Immanuel; not another is good  
\p like him. Hereafter Immanuel again to earth  
\p will come; we all shall see. Immanuel aloud  
\p will speak; then all the dead, men, women, children, all  
\p alive shall become. Immanuel will say “What hast thou done?  
\p What has thou done? thou good hast done? Thou  
\p to me come to heaven. Thou evil hast done?  
\p thou far go, very far go away.”  
\c 15  
\m \bd Giru ŋinda kagil ginyi; inda warawara yanani;\bd*  
\m \bd giru Baiame yili ginyi. Baiame yalwuŋa murruba;\bd*  
\m \bd ŋeane kanuŋo warawara yanani. Wīnungulla: kamil\bd*  
\m \bd ŋaia yal goalda; giru ŋaia goalda. Immanuel ŋirribatai\bd*  
\m \bd yarine, gūnagulladi taongo. Kanuŋo giwir kagil ginyi:\bd*  
\m \bd Immanuel ŋandil murruba; Immanuel baluni, giwir\bd*  
\m \bd moron gigigo.\bd*  
\p Truly thou bad hast become; thou astry hast gone;  
\p truly God angry is. God always is good;  
\p we all astray have gone. Hearken; not  
\p I lies tell; truth I tell. Immanuel from above  
\p came down, from heaven to earth. All men bad are become;  
\p Immanuel only is good; Immanuel died, men  
\p alive for to be.  
\c 16  
\m \bd Yeladu Baiame goalda; “Ŋindai, kanuŋo giwir,\bd*  
\m \bd kurria kagil gigle, berūdi warraia; ŋeane murru\bd*  
\m \bd ŋurrile. Kamil ŋaia yili gigla. Murruba Immanuel\bd*  
\m \bd baluni.” Yeladu Immanuel goalda: “Taiyanuŋa ŋununda\bd*  
\m \bd kanuŋo ŋindai iŋgil, īla ŋaia ŋindai tubbiamulle.”\bd*  
\p Now God saith: “Ye, all men,  
\p cease bad to be, turn ye; we will be  
\p reconciled. Not I angry am. Good Immanuel  
\p died.” Now Immanuel saith: “Come unto me  
\p all ye weary, then I you will cause to rest.”  
\p  
\m \bd Inda taiyanuŋa Immanuelgo.\bd*  
\p You come to Immanuel.  
\c 17  
\m \bd Giwir ŋuddelona\bd*  
\m \bd Littraga: bain dinna tuŋgōr, ŋurribu bain ge bain;\bd*  
\m \bd kamil yanelina. Paul, Barnaba ellibu, aro yanani. paul\bd*  
\m \bd goaldone; baindūl ŋerma wīnūŋailone. Paul kaia\bd*  
\m \bd ŋummildone, kakuldone, “Waria ŋurriba dinnaga.”\bd*  
\m \bd tuŋōrdūl parine, yanani ellibu.\bd*  
\p A man dwelt  
\p at Lystra; with sick foot diseased, very ill indeed;  
\p not he could walk. Paul, Barnabas also there came. Paul  
\p was speaking; the lame man him was hearing. Paul earnestly  
\p looked, he cried aloud “stand upright on feet.”  
\p The lame man leapt, walked also.  
\c 18  
\m \bd Burulabu giwir ŋummi, goe “Ŋipai!” Kākūldone\bd*  
\m \bd “Baiame bular yarine yealokwai giwir.” Paul, Barnaba\bd*  
\m \bd ellibu, bunnaŋunne, kakuldone, “Kurria! Kamil ŋeane\bd*  
\m \bd Baiame; ŋeane giwir yealokwai ŋindai. Ŋeane guiye\bd*  
\m \bd murru ŋurriŋillone. Ŋeane murru goalda burulabu;\bd*  
\m \bd kurria ŋindai yealo kagil gigle: berudi warraia,\bd*  
\m \bd ŋummilla Baiame moron. Baiame gīr gūnagulla, taon,\bd*  
\m \bd burul kolle, kanuŋo minnaminnabul gimobi. Baiame\bd*  
\m \bd yalwuŋa Baiame.”\bd*  
\p All the people saw, they wondered, they cried aloud  
\p “Gods two are come down like men.” Paul, Barnabas  
\p also ran, cired aloud “Have done! not we  
\p gods; we men like you. We glad  
\p become, we sorry become, we angry become, again we  
\p are reconciled. We good tell to all;  
\p cease ye any more evil to be; turn ye  
\p look to God the living. God verily heaven, earth  
\p the great water, all, everything made. God  
\p always is God (the same ever.”)  
\c 19  
\m \fig Kangaroo|src="Kangaroo.JPG" size="col" ref="GURRE KAMILAROI 19:0" \fig*  
\p b bundar.  
\c 20  
\m \fig Emu|src="Emu.JPG" size="col" ref="GURRE KAMILAROI 20:0" \fig*  
\p d dīnoun.  
\c 21  
\m \fig Man|src="Man.JPG" size="col" ref="GURRE KAMILAROI 21:0" \fig*  
\p g giwīr.  
\c 22  
\m \fig Woman|src="Woman.JPG" size="col" ref="GURRE KAMILAROI 22:0" \fig*  
\p i īnar.  
\c 23  
\m \fig Sheep|src="Sheep.JPG" size="col" ref="GURRE KAMILAROI 23:0" \fig*  
\p j jimba.  
\c 24  
\m \fig Duck|src="Duck.JPG" size="col" ref="GURRE KAMILAROI 24:0" \fig*  
\p k karāŋi.  
\c 25  
\m \fig Bird|src="Bird.JPG" size="col" ref="GURRE KAMILAROI 25:0" \fig*  
\p m mullion.  
\c 26  
\m \fig Snake|src="Snake.JPG" size="col" ref="GURRE KAMILAROI 26:0" \fig*  
\p n nūrai.  
\c 27  
\m \fig Pelican|src="Pelican.JPG" size="col" ref="GURRE KAMILAROI 27:0" \fig*  
\p ŋ ŋārūmnōn  
\c 28  
\m \fig Spear|src="Spear.JPG" size="col" ref="GURRE KAMILAROI 28:0" \fig*  
\p p pīlar.  
\c 29  
\m \fig Tree|src="Tree.JPG" size="col" ref="GURRE KAMILAROI 29:0" \fig*  
\p t tulu.  
\c 30  
\m \fig Crow|src="Crow.JPG" size="col" ref="GURRE KAMILAROI 30:0" \fig*  
\p w wāru.  
\c 31  
\m \fig Horse|src="Horse.JPG" size="col" ref="GURRE KAMILAROI 31:0" \fig*  
\p y yaraman.  